# @PROJECT_NAME@

STM32 @STM32_CHIP@ project on stm32-sdk @SDK_VERSION@ — SSD1306 128×64 OLED
display driven over I2C1 with a static title and a live uptime counter.

## SDK rules (must follow)

- CMSIS only, HAL/LL forbidden.
- C++20 (gnu++20), C11 (gnu11).
- MMIO access through `driver::reg::set/clear/write/read/get/modify` only.
- No raw pointers to peripherals — references (`GPIO_TypeDef&`).
- Configs without defaults — every field must be explicit.
- `GpioConfig` is an aggregate; wrap in `gpio({...})` for compile-time validation.
- Trailing comma after the last designated initializer to keep clang-format multi-line.

## Build / flash

```bash
stmtool build --native
stmtool flash
stmtool sdk update          # if [sdk] version = "develop"
```

## SDK reference

- Documentation: <https://khosta77.github.io/stm32-sdk/>
- SSD1306: <https://khosta77.github.io/stm32-sdk/sensors/ssd1306/>

## This template

Initializes an SSD1306 module on I2C1, draws a title and a counter, flushes
the framebuffer once per second.

### Pinout

| Function | Pin | Notes |
|----------|-----|-------|
| I2C1 SCL | PB6 | AF4, open-drain, pull-up |
| I2C1 SDA | PB7 | AF4, open-drain, pull-up |

I2C clock: 400 kHz. SSD1306 address: `0x3C` (7-bit; 8-bit write `0x78`).

### Connect the OLED

| OLED pin | STM32 pin |
|----------|-----------|
| VCC | 3.3 V (some modules accept 5 V — check the silkscreen) |
| GND | GND |
| SCL | PB6 |
| SDA | PB7 |

If the display is at `0x3D` instead of `0x3C`, change `addr = 0x3D` in the
`Ssd1306::Config`. The
[`bare-metal/i2c-scan`](https://github.com/khosta77/stm32-sdk/tree/develop/templates/bare-metal/i2c-scan)
template can confirm the actual address.

### What `main.cpp` does

1. In `__initialize_hardware()`: enable GPIOB and I2C1 clocks.
2. In `taskDisplay`: wait 200 ms for the panel to stabilize, call
   `g_oled.init()`.
3. Loop: clear framebuffer, draw three header lines and a `uptime: Ns`
   counter, call `flush()`. Wait 1000 ms.

The full framebuffer is 1024 bytes; `flush()` over 400 kHz I2C takes ~25 ms.

### Expected screen output

```
STM32 SDK
SSD1306 128x64
I2C @ 400 kHz


uptime: 12s
```

The bottom counter increments by one per second.

### How to verify

1. Flash the board.
2. Within ~200 ms after power-up, the display should light up.
3. The title text is static; only the `uptime:` line changes.
4. If the screen stays dark:
   - Run `bare-metal/i2c-scan` and confirm the SSD1306 address.
   - Check VCC voltage — some modules require 5 V despite labeling.
   - Verify pull-ups on SCL/SDA (most modules include them).

### When to extend

Add `g_oled.setPixel(x, y, on)` calls to draw graphics. For larger fonts or
anti-aliasing, render off-line and write into the framebuffer via `setPixel`.
